<section xml:id="sect-derivative-exp-log">
<title>Derivatives of exponential and logarithmic functions</title>

<p>Sketch a graph of the <em>exponential (growth)</em> function <m>f(x) = e^{x}</m>.

Using its graph, we can make some observations about properties of the derivative of the function.  The following questions might help with what comes next.
<ul>
<li><p>Is the graph increasing or decreasing?</p></li>
<li><p>Is the graph getting steeper, shallower, or maybe something else?</p></li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>Repeat with the \emph{exponential (decay)} function <m>g(x) = e^{-x}</m>, below.

<em>Interestingly</em> we can't get very far using the limit definition of the derivative for either of these calculations without some extra work on the side.</p>

<p>A derivative encodes a lot of information about the function it came from.  This can be useful to learn about important features of the graph of a function or to solve very important math and statistics problems\footnote{Finding trend lines (or curves) for scatterplots \emph{is} a calculus problem.}. This is all tied to how we think of or visualize the role of <m>m</m> in the equation <m>y = mx + b</m>, the graph of a straight line.</p>

<p>Find the slope of the tangent line to <m>f(x) = e^{x}</m> at <m>x_0 = 0</m>? And the equation to the tangent line?</p>

<p>What about at <m>x_0 = 1</m>?</p>

<p>%Are there <m>x</m>-values for which the tangent line to <m>f(x) = e^{x}</m> is ever horizontal? Or vertical?
%\vspace{2in}</p>

<p>We can confirm this later, but a general rule for exponential functions is that for a constant <m>c</m>, <me>\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(e^{cx}\right) = ce^{cx}.</me></p>

<p>Combining this new rule with earlier rules, find the following few derivatives.
<ul>
<li><p><m>f'(x)</m> for <m>f(x) = x^2 + e^{2x}</m></p></li>
<li><p><m>\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(1 - \dfrac{1}{x^2} + e^{-x}\right)</m></p></li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>Since we've discussed the exponential, we better mention the natural logarithm.  Again a graph is a good place to start.

<ul>
<li><p><m>f'(x)</m> for <m>f(x) = \ln(x) + e^{0.5x} - \dfrac{2}{x^6}</m></p></li>
<li><p><m>\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(\ln(cx)\right)</m> where  <m>c</m> is a constant\footnote{Try using rules for logarithms to help with <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}\left(\ln(x^c)\right)</m>, for constant <m>c</m>.
</p></li>
