</p>

<p>In summary, we have the following facts.</p>

<p>
Finally, in some problems we need what are called \emph{higher-order} derivatives. We have to be careful how we write this, but the mechanics are nothing new.  For example, the second derivative can be written 
<me>f''(x) = \dfrac{d^2f}{dx^2} =  \dfrac{d^2}{dx^2}\Big(f(x)\Big).</me> To do this, we start small, 
<me>\dfrac{d^2}{dx^2}\Big(f(x)\Big) = \dfrac{d}{dx}\Big(\dfrac{d}{dx}\Big(f(x)\Big)\Big).</me> In words, we take the derivative, then take its derivative - using the exact same techniques.  </p>

<p>One thing to point out - it is perfectly fine to mix the prime and differential notation, the prime notation is a faster label, but the differential notation is useful when differentiating an explicit formula.  If we need a really high-order derivative, the primes become too difficult to count, so instead we often write something like <m>f^{(n)}(x) = \dfrac{d^n f}{dx^n}</m> for some number <m>n</m>, but to be honest we won't really need to go much past a second- or third-order derivative for most purposes.</p>

<p><ul>
<li><p><m>f'(x)</m> and <m>f''(x)</m> for <m>f(x) = \ln(x) + e^{0.5x} - \dfrac{2}{x^6}</m></p></li>
<li><p><m>g'(x)</m>, <m>g''(x)</m> and <m>g'''(x)</m> for <m>g(x) = x^2 + e^x</m>.</p></li>
</ul></p>
